m—that might seem like polar opposites, but each offered pointed responses to containment culture. This book takes a fresh look at such directors as Nicholas Ray, John Ford, and Orson Welles, while giving readers a new appreciation for the depth and artistry of 1950s Hollywood films.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aCold War in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / General.2bisacsh  aAmerican film, 1950s, postwar, postwar period, containment culture, traditional family values, tradition, communism, communist sympathizers, blacklisted, entertainment industry, filmmakers, actors, Alfred Hitchcock, Stanley Kubrick, resistance, oppression, Cold War, Russia, melodrama, science fiction, 1950s Hollywood, Hollywood.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197882096840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978820968423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978820968/original  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK